## 6. Threshold & Configuration Management

Thresholds represent static, human-defined configurations (e.g., "Max Temperature is 24Â°C").
Rather than fracturing threshold configurations across multiple database collections, the system utilizes a Shared Infrastructure Data Model `(BuildingThresholdModel)`.

This central document contains nested "slices" for each domain:

.code lang:{json}
    {
      "buildingId": "HQ_01",
      "temperature": { "maxTemp": 24, "minTemp": 18 },
      "peopleCount": { "maxPeople": 50 }
    }

.mermaid
    sequenceDiagram
        participant Admin as Frontend Dashboard
        participant TC as Threshold Controller
        participant Module as Domain Module (Facade)
        participant Service as Domain Service
        participant DB as MongoDB

        Admin->>TC: PATCH /thresholds/temperature/buildings/HQ
        TC->>Module: updateBuildingThreshold()
        Module->>Service: updateBuildingThresholds()

        Note over Service, DB: Service uses dot-notation to isolate its domain
        Service->>DB: findOneAndUpdate({ $set: { "temperature.maxTemp": 25 } })
        DB-->>Service: Updated Document
        Service-->>Admin: HTTP 200 OK

When a domain service updates its configuration, it utilizes strictly scoped MongoDB dot-notation (e.g., `$set: { 'temperature.maxTemp': 25 }`)
to ensure it does not corrupt the configurations of neighboring modules.
